WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.420
I'm hoping to convince you that EIFRE, it has a new function that should be explored further.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:09.020
These are my disclosures.

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:14.100
So my laboratory has been highly interested in leukemia stem cells.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:24.720
As we heard now several times, it's its role during MRD and the desire to eliminate this population that we know can lead to disease relapse.

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:38.100
So through this journey, we have found many different approaches that have led us to potentially selective targeting of leukemia stem cells without harming hematopoietic stem cells.

00:00:38.460 --> 00:00:44.840
But yet, still, we have the same problem that this population is difficult to eradicate.

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:55.440
One of the pathways that we're interested in is the interaction of the leukemia stem cell with the...

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:56.660
microenvironment.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:01:01.480
And this is where we explored a new function for EIFRE in this context.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:07.840
It was well known that EIFRE has a role in migration in solid tumors.

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:16.740
And it was thought that this role had to do with just the production of proteins that were involved in metastasis.

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:23.460
So EIFRE, the role that we all know and we're familiar with is the initiation of protein...

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:24.460
the initiation of...

00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:28.540
of translation and protein synthesis.

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:32.920
We also know that sometimes has preferred mRNA targets.

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:38.460
And these targets have to do with cell growth, survival, and angiogenesis.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:45.460
We also know that EIFRE is involved in mRNA transport from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.500
It's also known to regulate splicing.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:55.080
It's well known to be overexpressed in several cancers, including breast, prostate, lymphoma, leukemia.

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:57.120
And also multiple myeloma.

00:01:57.940 --> 00:02:02.480
It has been reported several years ago, I was involved in this work as a post...

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:11.760
as a graduate student, so it's a long time ago, that in a subset of AML samples, EIFRE can be found localized in the nucleus.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:15.580
And this is a subset of M4s and M5s AMLs.

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:21.520
So because of that, it was always an interest of targeting EIFRE through time.

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:22.600
And...

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:24.820
And in a collaboration with...

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:32.820
Cathy Borden, that now is at Northwestern University, we started exploring if EIFRE could have a role

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:37.580
in the interaction of the leukemia stem cells with the microenvironment.

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:40.380
To this end, we used several tools.

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:48.160
We used genetic manipulation of EIFRE, in which we down-regulated EIFRE using CRISPR-Cas technology

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:52.200
or overexpressed EIFRE using vectors.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:54.980
Also, we used a pharmacological inhibition.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:54.980
Also, we used a pharmacological inhibition.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:54.980
Also, we used a pharmacological inhibition.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:54.980
Also, we used a pharmacological inhibition.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:55.060
Also, we used a pharmacological inhibition.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:59.760
This with ribavirin as a way to inhibit EIFRE.

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:07.100
The assays we used, we measured adhesion, invasion, colonization using a novel 3D system

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:13.900
that we have shown can stimulate the growth of leukemia stem cells inside this spheroid.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:17.020
And also, we used AML xenografts.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:22.140
What we found, as you can see here in blue, when you overexpress EIFRE,

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:24.980
you increase adhesion, invasion, and colonization of these...

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:26.340
these AML cells.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.600
If you down-regulate EIFRE, we decrease adhesion, invasion, and colonization,

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:37.580
suggesting, again, that EIFRE, if you manipulate EIFRE, you can control these processes.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.740
Importantly, if we use these cells in xenografts, we see that we can decrease the engraftment

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:48.440
of AML cells that down-regulate EIFRE.

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:54.960
And importantly, these animals can have an increased overall survival, as you can see in the picture.

00:03:54.980 --> 00:04:01.480
Also, if we look early on at the bone marrow of these mice, if you can see in the floor plots,

00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:05.980
it's very difficult to identify these leukemia cells in the bone marrow of these animals.

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:10.100
So somehow, these cells fail to find their home.

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:16.760
We also evaluated this using revivirin as a pharmacological inhibition of EIFRE,

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:23.300
and we found that when we treat the AML cells with revivirin, we decrease the invasion of these cells.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:24.800
And also, we found that when we treat the AML cells with revivirin, we decrease the invasion of these cells.

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:24.960
And also, if we look early on at the bone marrow of these mice, if you can see in the floor plots, it's very difficult to identify these leukemia cells in the bone marrow of these animals.

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:35.160
And also, in xenograft models, this is patient-derived xenografts, in this case showing AML55, you can see that we also improve overall survival of these mice.

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:48.320
So when we look at the machinery that is involved in the motility processes, specifically esrin, which plays a critical role in the cytoskeleton,

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:54.780
we found that when we immunoprecipitate EIFRE, we can bring the EIFRE to the bone marrow of these animals.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:05:01.060
bring down esrin and the translation machinery. And also when we pull down esrin, we bring down

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:08.380
the translation machinery and EIF-4E, as shown in this slide. We evaluated an assay. We had to

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:15.660
develop an assay to identify active translation using imaging, as shown here, using ribolase,

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:24.400
which is a biotinylated form of puromycin. So using this assay, you can see here that we can

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:32.800
co-localize the translation machinery, EIF-4E, esrin, CD44, all to the membrane of the cell,

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:36.980
right where the cell dopos are forming as the cell is trying to move.

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:47.620
And here is the measurement. When we use siRNA to esrin or EIF-4E, you can see we can decrease

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:54.020
that localization of the translation machinery to the membrane of the cell. And also when

00:05:54.020 --> 00:06:02.000
we downregulate either esrin or EIF-4E, suggesting that there is a very novel role of EIF-4E bringing

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.840
the whole translation machinery to the membrane to synthesize these mRNAs and initiate protein

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:16.480
translation on site to allow the movement of these cells. EIF-4E targeting has been tested

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:22.600
in several clinical trials, shown here, showing promise for EIF-4E targeting.

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:31.380
The reason that has not been continued was because EIF-4E ribavirin, in this case,

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:36.180
when combined with citarabine, citarabine can block the absorption of ribavirin.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:41.940
But there is still interest with combining ribavirin with other potential drugs.

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:47.600
So just to summarize, I hope I convinced you that there is still hope for targeting EIF-4E

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:53.580
or any of other partners interacting with EIF-4E at the membrane, because this could,

00:06:53.580 --> 00:07:00.240
in fact, avoid the interaction of leukemia stem cells with the microenvironment and allow for

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:06.880
better targeting of these cells. And just thank you for your attention. And this is my group.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:11.260
We still celebrate Day of the Dead as a good Mexican. Thank you very much.
